The reference distribution for producer j is built by simulating
\code{iter} random masks at the same trial count \code{trial_counts[j]},
mirroring the \code{genMask()} construction of Schmitz, Rougier, &
Yzerbyt (2024):
\enumerate{
\item Sample \code{trial_counts[j]} stimulus ids from \code{1:n_pool} without
replacement when \code{trial_counts[j] <= n_pool} (the canonical case
for both 2IFC and Brief-RC), with replacement otherwise.
\item Sample \code{trial_counts[j]} responses uniformly from \verb{\{-1, +1\}}.
\item Collapse \code{response} by \code{stim} via \code{mean()} (Brief-RC duplicate-
stim rule).
\item Build the mask: \code{noise_matrix[, unique_stims] \%*\% mean_response / n_unique_stims}.
\item Apply \code{mask} (if supplied) and compute the Frobenius norm.
}

The per-producer z-score is \code{(norm_j - median(ref)) / mad(ref)},
using the reference matched to producer j's trial count. Producers
sharing a trial count share a reference.

Trial-count matching closes a calibration gap in canonical
\code{rcicr::generateReferenceDistribution2IFC()}, which uses the full
pool size for the reference even when individual producers see only
a subset (relevant for Brief-RC).

\strong{Sampling regime.} The reference simulation needs to mirror the
regime the experimenter used. Two questions matter:
\enumerate{
\item \emph{Within-trial}: each Brief-RC trial shows \code{m} distinct pool items
(e.g. m=12 for Brief-RC 12), so within a single trial sampling
is always without replacement. This is implicit in the data
format and does not need a function argument.
\item \emph{Across-trials}: pool items can or cannot reappear on later
trials, depending on whether the experimenter sampled the pool
